WEBVTT

00:01.752 --> 00:03.253
[ Exhales sharply ]

00:03.253 --> 00:04.630
[ Whistles ]

00:04.630 --> 00:07.257
Wow. You are staring
very intensely at your phone.

00:07.257 --> 00:08.467
Yeah.
Don't listen to what

00:08.467 --> 00:10.302
the eighth graders say
about the way you dress.

00:10.302 --> 00:12.054
You are making
a fashion statement.

00:12.054 --> 00:14.389
What? Oh, no. I'm preparing
to do a FaceTime call

00:14.389 --> 00:15.766
with my sister.
It's her birthday.

00:15.766 --> 00:17.976
Oh, my gosh.
Can I finally meet her?

00:17.976 --> 00:20.270
Yeah, s-sure,
but just a warning --

00:20.270 --> 00:22.189
she can be really intense.
Really?

00:22.189 --> 00:23.857
Like, how so?
I don't know.

00:23.857 --> 00:25.442
She's just, like,
over the top.

00:25.442 --> 00:28.111
Like, kind of no self-awareness,
just really nosy.

00:28.111 --> 00:29.821
She's just a lot.
Got it.

00:29.821 --> 00:31.615
Well, thanks
for the warning.
[ Fingers snap ]

00:31.615 --> 00:33.742
Time to meet your sister
from another mister.

00:33.742 --> 00:36.620
Okay. [ Sighs ]
Alright.

00:36.620 --> 00:39.039
[ <i>FaceTime ringing</i> ]

00:39.039 --> 00:40.624
[ <i>Ding</i> ]

00:40.624 --> 00:42.292
Hey.
<i>Hey.</i>

00:42.292 --> 00:44.253
Hey.
Happy birthday.

00:44.253 --> 00:45.712
Happy birthday,
Ayesha!

00:45.712 --> 00:47.089
That's my friend,
Jacob.

00:47.089 --> 00:48.257
Great to meet you!

00:48.257 --> 00:49.633
<i>Yeah, nice to meet you, too.</i>

00:49.633 --> 00:50.676
[ Laughs ]
I'm sorry.

00:50.676 --> 00:52.219
I should've turned
the volume down.

00:52.219 --> 00:54.763
Her voice --
it just carries, you know?

00:54.763 --> 00:56.348
So, any fun plans?

00:56.348 --> 00:58.350
<i>Uh, yeah, I might go out</i>
<i>with some friends.</i>

00:58.350 --> 00:59.768
<i>They just got married, so...</i>

00:59.768 --> 01:02.020
[ Chuckles ]
Ooh. TMI.

01:02.020 --> 01:03.897
You know? It's like, "Why are
you telling me all of this?

01:03.897 --> 01:06.066
I am not your therapist."

01:06.066 --> 01:07.776
[ Sighs ]
Well, you know what?

01:07.776 --> 01:09.319
I hope you have
a good one.

01:09.319 --> 01:11.238
<i>Yeah.</i>
<i>Uh, thanks for calling.</i>

01:11.238 --> 01:12.406
Yeah. Okay.
<i>Bye.</i>

01:12.406 --> 01:14.575
Bye. Bye. Oh, my God.
She is impossible

01:14.575 --> 01:16.368
to get off the phone with.

01:16.368 --> 01:18.036
Every call is like the length
between Netflix seasons.

01:18.036 --> 01:19.329
It's like -- I don't
remember what happened

01:19.329 --> 01:20.747
on the last season
of "Stranger Things."

01:20.747 --> 01:22.291
That was 10 years ago.

01:22.291 --> 01:25.544
Yeah. I-I don't know.
I think she seemed nice.

01:25.544 --> 01:28.088
I could see us really,
you know, hitting it off.

01:28.088 --> 01:30.716
And she just holds you captive
and she won't let you get away

01:30.716 --> 01:32.843
and she just
goes on and on and on.

01:32.843 --> 01:35.012
And right when you think it's
over, she just keeps going.

01:35.012 --> 01:37.014
You know?
And I have a story for you.

01:37.014 --> 01:39.391
You might want to sit
down, 'cause this one
has a lot of turns.

01:39.391 --> 01:41.101
So...

01:41.101 --> 01:43.520
[ Maker's "Hold'em" playing ]

01:43.520 --> 01:51.236
♪♪

01:53.322 --> 01:55.657
And then Zach brought me
breakfast in bed,

01:55.657 --> 01:58.535
which is something I only
thought happened in movies.

01:58.535 --> 02:00.537
And that led to some
other stuff that happens

02:00.537 --> 02:02.748
in, you know,
other kind of movies.

02:02.748 --> 02:07.252
All I'm saying is
my relaysh is sensaysh.

02:07.252 --> 02:09.546
That means my relationship
is sensational.

02:09.546 --> 02:12.924
Well, Gary hasn't made
any plans that I know of yet.

02:12.924 --> 02:15.927
So just in case he turns out
to be a total <i>gavone,</i>

02:15.927 --> 02:18.889
I called Barclay Prime
and made a backup rez.

02:18.889 --> 02:20.766
Rez--
Zervation.

02:20.766 --> 02:22.601
I know how
abbreviations work...

02:22.601 --> 02:24.186
Mr. C.

02:24.186 --> 02:27.230
Hmm. Gerald and I have
been so preoccupied,

02:27.230 --> 02:28.815
we forgot it was
Valentine's Day.

02:28.815 --> 02:31.401
Didn't make a reservation.
Now everything is booked up.

02:31.401 --> 02:33.362
Girl, we're gonna end up
going to Popeyes.

02:33.362 --> 02:35.113
You should try
airport restaurants.

02:35.113 --> 02:37.407
Yeah, people don't realize
that you can make
a reservation there.

02:37.407 --> 02:39.284
It's like the best-kept secret
in the city.

02:39.284 --> 02:41.662
That's true,
and Airport Chickie N' Pete's

02:41.662 --> 02:43.789
has the best lobster roll
in Philly.

02:43.789 --> 02:45.248
You can quote me on that.

02:45.248 --> 02:46.875
-Gregory.
-Hmm?

02:46.875 --> 02:50.379
So, how's your...relaysh going
with your student's parent?

02:50.379 --> 02:52.005
Worst possible way
to phrase that.

02:52.005 --> 02:53.965
<i>Former</i> student's parent.
And it's going well.

02:53.965 --> 02:56.259
It's me and Amber's
first Valentine's Day,
so I want to get it right.

02:56.259 --> 02:57.969
Bought three gifts,
and I'm still trying

02:57.969 --> 02:59.137
to decide which two
to send back.

02:59.137 --> 03:00.847
Oh.
Ooh, nail biter.

03:00.847 --> 03:03.183
Well, I do fancy myself
quite the gift-giver,

03:03.183 --> 03:05.394
so if you need help kinda --
No.

03:05.394 --> 03:07.521
[Singsong voice]
Hello, everyone!

03:07.521 --> 03:10.232
[Normal voice] So, I found this
Valentine in my mailbox,

03:10.232 --> 03:12.192
and it's from
"a secret admirer."

03:12.192 --> 03:14.194
Candy heart
with my name on it.

03:14.194 --> 03:15.237
Is this from
one of you guys?

03:17.864 --> 03:19.866
My Valentine's Day plans?

03:19.866 --> 03:23.161
Well, Mo is coming by after
school with a surprise gift.

03:23.161 --> 03:24.538
So I have no idea
what to expect

03:24.538 --> 03:26.164
since I don't know him
that well,

03:26.164 --> 03:28.333
but based on what I <i>do</i> know,

03:28.333 --> 03:32.003
he has easy access
to shipping materials.

03:32.003 --> 03:34.506
And I always need tape, so...

03:34.506 --> 03:38.385
Aww. Happy Valentine's Day
to you, too, Iggy.

03:38.385 --> 03:41.221
Yeah, you might
see me tonight.

03:41.221 --> 03:42.639
I already have
car insurance!

03:44.599 --> 03:46.435
Hey, Tristan.

03:46.435 --> 03:49.229
Tristan's a hot dad in the
91st percentile of hot dads.

03:49.229 --> 03:51.648
He's got a kid in Jacob's class,
and he's handsome.

03:51.648 --> 03:54.109
He looks like men do
before they have kids.

03:54.109 --> 03:55.444
I'm here to complain.

03:55.444 --> 03:56.570
Oh.

03:58.196 --> 04:00.240
Please continue.
I take umbrage with the fact

04:00.240 --> 04:02.284
that Mr. Hill,
a white teacher,

04:02.284 --> 04:04.411
is teaching Black history
to my son

04:04.411 --> 04:06.788
and other students
during Black History Month.

04:06.788 --> 04:08.874
Okay, Mr. Umbrage. What do
you want <i>me</i> to do about it?

04:08.874 --> 04:11.209
You could have a Black teacher
teaching it.

04:11.209 --> 04:12.919
Or we could keep having
Mr. Hill teach it,

04:12.919 --> 04:14.379
because if you think
about it,

04:14.379 --> 04:16.173
underpaying a white teacher
to teach Black history

04:16.173 --> 04:17.632
is almost reparation.

04:20.385 --> 04:23.138
Fine. Well, I can't do anything
until I observe for myself.

04:26.516 --> 04:29.019
Never heard you utter a word.
Now you bust out "umbrage."

04:29.019 --> 04:30.228
[ Scoffs ]

04:30.228 --> 04:31.897
Miss Teagues?
Yes?

04:31.897 --> 04:35.150
Did you get my valentine?
The heart candy?

04:35.150 --> 04:37.152
Oh. Yes. Yes.

04:37.152 --> 04:39.279
Um, the one in my mailbox.

04:39.279 --> 04:41.531
Yes, I did get
your valentine.

04:41.531 --> 04:44.743
Thank you, Donnie.
That was very, very kind of you.

04:44.743 --> 04:46.828
What if you made
another valentine

04:46.828 --> 04:48.997
and you gave it to someone
in your desk pod?

04:48.997 --> 04:51.124
Eh. They're girls.

04:51.124 --> 04:52.167
I need a <i>woman.</i>

04:53.376 --> 04:55.796
So, this happens
from time to time.

04:55.796 --> 04:57.964
Students form a real bond
with teachers,

04:57.964 --> 04:59.966
which is understandable,
but sometimes

04:59.966 --> 05:03.595
it get confused
and turns into a little crush.

05:03.595 --> 05:06.973
Plus, I look like a giant kid,
so they get confused even more.

05:06.973 --> 05:09.476
Internet sucks today, right?
[ Laughs ]

05:09.476 --> 05:11.895
Not one scandal?
Do better, Twitter.

05:11.895 --> 05:14.481
[ Marker squeaking ]
You teenagers today

05:14.481 --> 05:16.274
are so boring
paying all that attention.

05:16.274 --> 05:18.443
Class, if you are wondering
why Principal Coleman

05:18.443 --> 05:20.612
is sitting in today,
fret not.

05:20.612 --> 05:22.322
It's just a standard,

05:22.322 --> 05:25.200
run-of-the-mill
classroom observation.

05:25.200 --> 05:28.745
There's absolutely...
nothing to worry about.

05:28.745 --> 05:30.413
I'm a little worried.

05:30.413 --> 05:34.376
This is very un-standard
and out-of-the-mill for Ava.

05:34.376 --> 05:35.961
We all know how we have
been taught to think

05:35.961 --> 05:38.380
about Martin Luther King Jr.
and Malcolm X,

05:38.380 --> 05:40.632
but they were actually
much more similar

05:40.632 --> 05:42.509
in their philosophies
by the end of their lives

05:42.509 --> 05:44.177
than they were
at the beginning.

05:44.177 --> 05:46.263
Yeah, I mean, people said
they didn't get along,

05:46.263 --> 05:48.014
but that's not true.

05:48.014 --> 05:50.100
Talk about it.
Anybody else know anything

05:50.100 --> 05:51.643
about their
real relationship?

05:51.643 --> 05:54.187
They almost swapped
philosophies towards the end.

05:54.187 --> 05:56.648
Oh, for real?
For real.

05:56.648 --> 05:58.775
White people wanted to pit them
against each other.

05:58.775 --> 06:00.151
That is right, Paul.

06:00.151 --> 06:02.362
See, history is constantly
being rewritten.

06:02.362 --> 06:03.822
[ Phone locks ]
That is why you need to

06:03.822 --> 06:05.365
question everything, okay?

06:05.365 --> 06:08.118
You should even question me,
a white teacher.

06:08.118 --> 06:09.953
[ Students murmur ]

06:09.953 --> 06:12.372
Okay.
[ Clears throat ]

06:16.334 --> 06:18.712
Did I black out and
rearrange my desk again?

06:18.712 --> 06:21.548
[ Rhythmic knocking on door ]

06:21.548 --> 06:23.258
I saved this for you.

06:23.258 --> 06:24.676
Oh...

06:24.676 --> 06:27.846
Extra napkins are in
the top left drawer.

06:27.846 --> 06:31.141
Uh -- Excuse me, Donnie.
Did you straighten up my desk?

06:31.141 --> 06:32.559
I did.

06:32.559 --> 06:34.811
I see a real future
with us.

06:38.356 --> 06:42.152
So, I made reservations
at the airport Cibo Bistro.

06:42.152 --> 06:43.737
Got us a table
right by the window

06:43.737 --> 06:45.655
so we could see
the planes take off.

06:45.655 --> 06:48.116
Yeah.
Gerald loves to see them go.

06:48.116 --> 06:50.452
Well, I still have
no word from Gary.

06:50.452 --> 06:52.996
I swear, if I find out
he is dipping his chip

06:52.996 --> 06:55.707
into someone else's dip, it'll
be the last time he sells chips.

06:55.707 --> 06:57.751
He will come through.

06:57.751 --> 06:59.711
Oh, he better, or I'm pulling
the plug on him like we did

06:59.711 --> 07:01.713
my Aunt Denise,
and that sure woke <i>her</i> up,

07:01.713 --> 07:03.798
so maybe it'll make
Gary come around.

07:03.798 --> 07:05.550
Well, girl,
I'll see you later.

07:05.550 --> 07:08.261
I've got to go look into
the TSA airport check-in thing.

07:08.261 --> 07:10.138
Well, you know
you have to buy a ticket

07:10.138 --> 07:12.098
to get through
airport security, right?

07:12.098 --> 07:14.225
Wait. What -- Ooh!

07:14.225 --> 07:17.270
I have been cruises only
for the past two decades.

07:17.270 --> 07:19.731
That's why I told you.
Now I'm back to square one.

07:19.731 --> 07:21.441
Ooh!
Sorry.

07:21.441 --> 07:22.734
Janine:
Hey, Melissa? Hey.

07:22.734 --> 07:24.527
Yeah.
Can I get your help
with something?

07:24.527 --> 07:26.821
Yeah.
Okay, so,
I have this kid Donnie,

07:26.821 --> 07:28.448
and he has
a little crush on me.

07:28.448 --> 07:30.700
I thought it would blow over,
but he just won't let up.

07:30.700 --> 07:33.536
I mean, he's always going out
of his way to try to impress me

07:33.536 --> 07:35.789
and, like, fixing stuff up
in my classroom.

07:35.789 --> 07:37.457
And I don't even know.

07:37.457 --> 07:39.501
He's, like, sometimes
just staring at me.

07:39.501 --> 07:41.127
You know what I mean?

07:41.127 --> 07:43.171
And to get my attention,
he does this little knock thing.

07:43.171 --> 07:44.464
Eh, I don't know.
I mean, I thought --

07:44.464 --> 07:45.924
I thought it was
nothing at first,

07:45.924 --> 07:49.052
but now I think he might have
actual feelings for me.

07:49.052 --> 07:51.471
Yeah, no. That's just --
That's puppy love, Dolittle.

07:51.471 --> 07:53.556
It'll pass.

07:53.556 --> 07:55.558
Look, I-I do <i>not</i> think
that it'll pass,

07:55.558 --> 07:58.978
and I am so glad you
finally know that he likes you!

07:58.978 --> 08:01.815
Mm-hmm. Yeah, I mean, it's
pretty obvious at this point.

08:01.815 --> 08:03.191
Ohh!
I am so relieved!

08:03.191 --> 08:05.151
I thought I was
the only one who knew,

08:05.151 --> 08:07.362
and I really wanted to tell you,
but I couldn't because,

08:07.362 --> 08:09.906
you know, he's my friend, too,
and bro code.

08:09.906 --> 08:12.200
Wow. Didn't know you two
were tight like that.

08:12.200 --> 08:14.536
I mean,
we're only best friends.

08:14.536 --> 08:16.371
What?
When he bought
all that candy,

08:16.371 --> 08:18.164
that's when I put
the pieces together.

08:18.164 --> 08:19.833
What do you mean
"bought all that candy"?

08:19.833 --> 08:21.501
It was just one little
heart candy.

08:21.501 --> 08:23.920
No! Remember? Gregory
bought like so much candy.

08:24.879 --> 08:26.423
Gregory?
Yeah.

08:26.423 --> 08:28.341
I was talking about Donnie
in my class.

08:30.635 --> 08:33.430
Yes. Yeah. So was I.

08:33.430 --> 08:36.474
Donnie. Donald.
Yeah.

08:36.474 --> 08:38.059
Um, I actually think I'm --

08:38.059 --> 08:40.311
I am really late
for a meeting with --

08:40.311 --> 08:41.604
No, no. No, no, no.
You're lying.

08:41.604 --> 08:43.148
You -- You said Gregory.

08:43.148 --> 08:44.524
Like, <i>our</i> Gregory?
The school's Gregory?

08:44.524 --> 08:46.317
I don't -- You know what?
Actually, I don't

08:46.317 --> 08:48.778
even know anymore.
I forgot. Um...

08:48.778 --> 08:50.405
Gregory likes me?

08:50.405 --> 08:52.907
Which you totally
already knew, right?

08:57.537 --> 08:59.456
So Gregory told you this?

08:59.456 --> 09:00.623
Not exactly, but when
I called him on it and said,

09:00.623 --> 09:02.208
"Do you have feelings
for Janine?"

09:02.208 --> 09:03.626
he, like, didn't answer.
Oh, God.

09:03.626 --> 09:05.378
That could mean anything.
Or nothing, really.

09:05.378 --> 09:07.172
But it's also the way
he pays attention to you.

09:07.172 --> 09:08.339
He knows all
of your interests.

09:08.339 --> 09:10.008
He's <i>always</i> around you.

09:10.008 --> 09:11.718
Oh, Jacob,
we work together!

09:11.718 --> 09:14.262
And what about the dancing at
the club I wasn't invited to?

09:14.262 --> 09:16.514
That -- See, that --
that was, uh --

09:16.514 --> 09:17.974
that was nothing.

09:17.974 --> 09:20.852
And, uh, it was fun.
It was just fun.

09:20.852 --> 09:23.313
Yeah, well, not to brag,
but I think I know
something about crushes.

09:23.313 --> 09:25.106
I wrote a 14-page
research paper in college

09:25.106 --> 09:26.941
about the psychological effects
of longing for someone

09:26.941 --> 09:28.818
and not acting on it.

09:28.818 --> 09:30.862
Gregory does not like me
like that, okay?

09:30.862 --> 09:32.697
We are just friends.

09:32.697 --> 09:35.450
He has a girlfriend, Amber,
who is so different from me.

09:35.450 --> 09:38.328
I mean, honestly.
Could not be <i>more</i> different.

09:38.328 --> 09:40.330
Gregory doesn't like me.

09:40.330 --> 09:43.792
Gregory...liking me?
That cannot be true.

09:43.792 --> 09:46.586
It has to be another one
of Jacob's theories,

09:46.586 --> 09:49.464
like the one he has about all
the teachers here disliking him,

09:49.464 --> 09:50.924
which is false.

09:50.924 --> 09:52.383
Only a handful of them do.

09:52.383 --> 09:54.844
Say, like, 30% to 60%.

09:54.844 --> 09:57.680
Unlike Phase One Tony Stark,

09:57.680 --> 10:00.809
Malcolm X and Martin Luther King
were both anti-capitalists.

10:02.393 --> 10:04.687
You seem a little shaky,
Mr. Hill.

10:04.687 --> 10:05.939
Are you good?
Oh, yeah.

10:05.939 --> 10:09.067
I'm good.
I am...totally fine.

10:11.486 --> 10:14.572
Ava has been
in my last three classes, okay?

10:14.572 --> 10:16.491
Either this is some
time-intensive prank,

10:16.491 --> 10:18.409
or I am getting fired...

10:18.409 --> 10:20.620
for teaching Black history.

10:20.620 --> 10:23.957
[ Scoffs ]
I flew too close to the sun.

10:23.957 --> 10:25.959
Like an anti-racist Icarus.

10:27.418 --> 10:29.254
Yes, uh, Principal Coleman?

10:29.254 --> 10:30.964
Just making sure you
don't leave out the part

10:30.964 --> 10:33.550
about Martin Luther King Jr.
wanting universal basic income.

10:33.550 --> 10:35.301
You mentioned it
two periods ago,

10:35.301 --> 10:37.053
but you forgot to
mention it last period.

10:37.053 --> 10:41.266
Uh, thank you, Ms. Coleman,
for publicly calling me in.

10:41.266 --> 10:42.934
You know what?
Let's course-correct.

10:42.934 --> 10:44.310
Everybody grab a partner.

10:44.310 --> 10:45.770
We are gonna do some
paired reading, okay?

10:45.770 --> 10:47.355
I think we've got
an odd number today,

10:47.355 --> 10:48.648
so there's gonna have to be
a group of three.

10:48.648 --> 10:50.066
Why don't you just pair
somebody up with me?

10:50.066 --> 10:51.359
[ Students gasp ]

10:51.359 --> 10:53.236
You want to...read?

10:53.236 --> 10:55.738
It be your own teachers,
don't it?

10:56.614 --> 10:59.450
[ Laughs loudly ] That's --
Oh, sorry.

10:59.450 --> 11:01.661
I was just thinking about
something Jacob said.

11:01.661 --> 11:03.538
It was zany, really.

11:03.538 --> 11:06.708
He said that someone likes me,
which I don't think they do.

11:06.708 --> 11:08.835
But, you know, what's
a surefire way to know
if someone likes you?

11:08.835 --> 11:10.962
Well, who did Jacob say
liked you?

11:10.962 --> 11:12.422
Oh, I don't want
to go into details.

11:12.422 --> 11:13.798
Yes, you do.
You brought it up.

11:13.798 --> 11:15.300
And why are we talking
about this?

11:15.300 --> 11:16.926
I thought you made a friend
for this.

11:16.926 --> 11:20.013
[Taunting]
♪ I know who it is ♪

11:20.013 --> 11:21.973
Okay, you know what?
You guys are right.
Let's not talk about it.

11:21.973 --> 11:23.141
It's Gregory!

11:24.392 --> 11:25.768
What?
W-Why would you guess that?

11:25.768 --> 11:27.562
'Cause it's
blatantly obvious.

11:27.562 --> 11:30.190
I mean,
he <i>absolutely</i> likes you.

11:30.190 --> 11:33.693
Although I think that workplace
romances are a terrible idea.

11:33.693 --> 11:36.613
Yeah. That's why I never
tried anything with him.

11:36.613 --> 11:38.990
Also, I have a boyfriend.
But mostly Barb's reason.

11:38.990 --> 11:40.658
So, wait. Everyone just --
just knows this?

11:40.658 --> 11:42.118
Yeah, y'all
the only two dummies

11:42.118 --> 11:43.661
that don't know
that you like each other.

11:43.661 --> 11:46.039
Whoa!
But you <i>do</i> like him, right?

11:46.039 --> 11:49.083
Despite you lack of swag,
height, and good outfits,

11:49.083 --> 11:51.419
he thinks you're cute,
but just don't do anything
nasty on school grounds,

11:51.419 --> 11:52.962
because if I can't,
then y'all can't.

11:52.962 --> 11:54.714
I-I can't believe
what I'm hearing.

11:54.714 --> 11:57.008
You know -- 'Cause
I-I-I can't like Gregory.
'Cause I like Maurice.

11:57.008 --> 11:59.385
Sweetheart, it is possible
to like two people

11:59.385 --> 12:01.054
at the same time.

12:01.054 --> 12:04.015
This is wild.
This cannot be a thing.

12:04.015 --> 12:05.975
You know, I am dating
Gregory's friend Maurice,

12:05.975 --> 12:07.518
and Gregory's dating Amber.

12:07.518 --> 12:08.978
Plus, we work together.

12:08.978 --> 12:10.605
So, then what would happen?

12:10.605 --> 12:13.316
We see each other
during the day <i>and</i> at night?

12:13.316 --> 12:15.485
We'd, you know,
tell each other stuff

12:15.485 --> 12:18.029
and feel comfortable together?
[ Chuckles ]

12:18.029 --> 12:19.989
Like, share
our deepest thoughts,

12:19.989 --> 12:21.991
and, you know...a life.

12:23.701 --> 12:26.204
It's gross, honestly.
Just...blegh.

12:30.291 --> 12:32.669
Zach, you can't be
setting up all this in here!

12:32.669 --> 12:34.254
Somebody should
really be monitoring

12:34.254 --> 12:35.922
what's allowed to go on
at this campus.

12:35.922 --> 12:37.423
Jacob has a free period,

12:37.423 --> 12:39.759
and I'm surprising him with
a Valentine's Day lunch.

12:39.759 --> 12:41.135
They get a free period?

12:41.135 --> 12:42.929
These teachers
are lazy as hell!

12:42.929 --> 12:45.014
We were just about to dive
into the rhetoric that MLK used

12:45.014 --> 12:46.224
in his
"I Have a Dream" speech.

12:46.224 --> 12:48.726
Wait. Are you
in Jacob's class?

12:48.726 --> 12:50.019
As, like, a student?

12:50.019 --> 12:51.396
No, I'm not a student,

12:51.396 --> 12:53.398
but thank you for noticing
my youthful glow.

12:53.398 --> 12:55.024
Some people think
I don't even <i>have</i> pores.

12:55.024 --> 12:57.318
I'm just observing because
I'm a very good principal.

12:57.318 --> 12:58.736
How many classes
have you observed?

12:58.736 --> 13:00.530
All of them. How am I
supposed to pass the final

13:00.530 --> 13:01.906
if I don't go
to every class?

13:01.906 --> 13:03.700
Sounds like you're doing
more than just observing.

13:03.700 --> 13:05.535
Sounds like you're actually
enjoying learning.

13:05.535 --> 13:07.537
I will kick your
Jacob-loving Saint Valentine ass

13:07.537 --> 13:09.330
right out of this school.
I hate learning.

13:09.330 --> 13:11.207
You just sound so passionate
and engaged.

13:11.207 --> 13:12.250
I'm confused.

13:13.918 --> 13:15.211
<i>I'm</i> confused.

13:15.211 --> 13:17.338
I never liked school.

13:17.338 --> 13:18.548
Got in the way
of college.

13:18.548 --> 13:20.216
[ Slurping ]

13:20.216 --> 13:21.843
Now here I am, soaking up
Black history lessons

13:21.843 --> 13:23.011
from Jacob of all people.

13:23.011 --> 13:24.721
No offense.
None taken.

13:24.721 --> 13:26.723
Do you think that now
that you've ma-toured,

13:26.723 --> 13:28.933
you're actually
interested in learning?

13:28.933 --> 13:30.184
That's interesting.

13:31.311 --> 13:33.521
Ugh!
Stop making good points.

13:33.521 --> 13:34.897
[ Keyboard clacking ]

13:34.897 --> 13:36.858
[ Rhythmic knocking ]

13:36.858 --> 13:38.318
Hey. You got a second?

13:38.318 --> 13:40.653
Yeah, my kids
are in gym, so...
Okay. Good.

13:42.363 --> 13:43.740
[ Clears throat ]

13:47.994 --> 13:50.747
Okay. I have something really
important I need to ask you.

13:50.747 --> 13:51.956
Okay.

13:53.666 --> 13:55.334
Did Jacob
already tell you?

13:55.334 --> 13:58.129
I mean, to be fair,
he didn't mean to.

13:58.129 --> 14:01.007
He thought I knew already,
which I didn't, so...

14:01.007 --> 14:03.134
Well, now that you do,
what do you think?

14:03.134 --> 14:04.761
You think
it's good enough?

14:04.761 --> 14:06.429
That's a weird way
to phrase it.

14:06.429 --> 14:08.306
I don't think it's about
if it's good enough.

14:08.306 --> 14:10.058
I just think it's, you know --
it's -- it's complicated.

14:10.058 --> 14:11.517
That's what I'm stuck on.

14:11.517 --> 14:13.061
It's actually
not that complicated.

14:13.061 --> 14:15.063
But it is, though, Gregory.
I mean, it also --

14:15.063 --> 14:17.440
It's ages 12 and up.
How complicated could it be?

14:17.440 --> 14:19.108
Wait -- S-- Mnh.

14:19.108 --> 14:21.027
Sorry. Wait. Just --
Time out. What?

14:23.237 --> 14:25.073
It's -- It's got
a lot of pieces,

14:25.073 --> 14:27.366
but complicated it is not.

14:27.366 --> 14:29.243
See, Amber's allergic
to <i>real</i> flowers,

14:29.243 --> 14:30.703
so it's a Lego set

14:30.703 --> 14:33.247
that you can build
into a bouquet of flowers.

14:33.247 --> 14:35.166
But if you think it's too much
or not enough --

14:35.166 --> 14:38.252
Wait. So, this is your
Valentine's Day gift for Amber?

14:38.252 --> 14:39.253
Yeah.

14:41.464 --> 14:43.424
This is the coolest
friggin' gift I've ever seen.

14:43.424 --> 14:45.593
Okay, good.
'Cause I was worried.

14:45.593 --> 14:47.220
<i>You</i> were worried?
<i>I</i> was worried.

14:47.220 --> 14:48.930
About what?
Doesn't matter.

14:48.930 --> 14:50.723
Okay.
Yeah, what does matter
is that I was right,

14:50.723 --> 14:52.266
and I will be
telling Jacob that.

14:52.266 --> 14:55.603
Unh-unh. Javon, sit down!
Thank you!

14:55.603 --> 14:56.687
What was that?

14:56.687 --> 14:58.356
That is so cool.

14:58.356 --> 14:59.857
She's gonna love it.

14:59.857 --> 15:00.900
Thanks.
Yeah.

15:07.949 --> 15:11.160
[ Whistling ]

15:12.495 --> 15:14.122
So, I didn't mean to tell you,
and I was feeling

15:14.122 --> 15:15.915
really bad about it at lunch,
but then I happened to walk by

15:15.915 --> 15:17.708
and I saw that you were having
a rather intense conversation,

15:17.708 --> 15:18.835
so if it went bad,
don't blame me,

15:18.835 --> 15:20.253
because, again,
I didn't mean to tell you,

15:20.253 --> 15:21.963
but if it went well,
give me credit, because --

15:21.963 --> 15:23.673
Do you want to shut up now
so that I can tell you?

15:23.673 --> 15:25.466
Yes.
Okay.

15:25.466 --> 15:26.717
So, everything's fine.

15:26.717 --> 15:28.261
In fact, everything
is <i>more</i> than fine

15:28.261 --> 15:29.846
because he really likes
Amber.

15:29.846 --> 15:32.515
So I'm off the hook.
In fact, there was never a hook.

15:32.515 --> 15:34.267
Or a line.
Or even a boat.

15:34.267 --> 15:36.269
So...yay.

15:36.269 --> 15:38.646
I'm sorry. I thought --
Wait. Are you sure?

15:38.646 --> 15:40.314
Yes.

15:40.314 --> 15:43.484
And why be sorry?
Everything's great.

15:43.484 --> 15:45.444
He got her
an amazing gift,

15:45.444 --> 15:48.156
the most romantic Legos
I've ever seen,

15:48.156 --> 15:50.116
so, obviously,
he's really into her,

15:50.116 --> 15:52.034
which means he's obviously
not into me.

15:52.034 --> 15:53.744
Well, people can like
more than one person.

15:53.744 --> 15:55.246
That's not what's
happening here.

15:55.246 --> 15:57.957
He really likes Amber.
And I'm really dating Mo.

15:59.709 --> 16:02.378
Well, I guess Gregory's
love language is gifts.

16:02.378 --> 16:04.589
<i>That's</i> why he doesn't respond
to my words of affirmation.

16:07.258 --> 16:09.468
So, I have another surprise
for you.

16:09.468 --> 16:11.220
[ Knock on door ]
Wait. Hold that thought.

16:11.220 --> 16:12.889
Um, okay.
Please don't fire me.

16:12.889 --> 16:14.640
I can't get bad news
while I'm eating.

16:14.640 --> 16:16.058
I have stress-induced IBS.

16:16.058 --> 16:17.977
No one's getting fired,
honey.

16:17.977 --> 16:21.022
Ava <i>is</i> the surprise.
Tell him the big news.

16:21.022 --> 16:24.025
Although I am one of the
century's greatest autodidacts,

16:24.025 --> 16:26.110
I found myself paying attention
in your class.

16:27.737 --> 16:29.322
I'll never get through this
if you're looking at me.

16:29.322 --> 16:30.656
Turn around.

16:32.617 --> 16:34.994
I'm going back to school,
I'm enrolling in night courses,

16:34.994 --> 16:36.579
and I might even get
the credential

16:36.579 --> 16:38.122
I'm supposed to have
to work here.

16:38.122 --> 16:41.709
Ava, that's -- Wait.
So I'm <i>not</i> getting fired?

16:41.709 --> 16:44.712
No! You're getting a raise!
In my teacher rankings.

16:44.712 --> 16:47.131
You and Janine were
battling it out for last place.

16:49.550 --> 16:50.718
Miss Teagues?

16:50.718 --> 16:53.846
Oh, hey.
Look, Donnie, um...

16:53.846 --> 16:56.682
Valentine's Day is our
most confusing holiday.

16:56.682 --> 16:58.559
Look, I know you <i>think</i>
you have feelings for me,

16:58.559 --> 17:01.187
but sometimes
when we think we --
Let me stop you.

17:01.187 --> 17:04.357
I don't think
I like you anymore.

17:04.357 --> 17:06.776
It's not you. It's me.

17:06.776 --> 17:08.694
Oh.
There's someone else.

17:12.990 --> 17:14.450
Can I have
my Valentine back?

17:14.450 --> 17:17.536
Of course. Yes.
Of course. Heh! Whew.

17:17.536 --> 17:20.873
I see I'm not
the only one.

17:20.873 --> 17:24.001
These are the ones I'm gonna
be giving out, but thank you.

17:24.001 --> 17:25.586
So I was like, "Malcolm X?

17:25.586 --> 17:27.672
More like 'Malcolm Y we gotta be
in this class so long?'"

17:27.672 --> 17:29.382
[ Laughter ]

17:29.382 --> 17:31.592
[ Laughter stops ]

17:31.592 --> 17:33.511
Oh. Hey, Dad.

17:33.511 --> 17:36.055
Paul and I were just discussing
today's Black history lesson.

17:36.055 --> 17:38.432
And I bet it was better
considering Mr. Hill
wasn't teaching it.

17:38.432 --> 17:40.935
Oh, he was teaching it,
and he's gonna continue to.

17:40.935 --> 17:42.895
Don't judge him
by the color of his skin

17:42.895 --> 17:44.939
or by the content
of his class.

17:44.939 --> 17:47.692
Wow. I just made that up!
[ Giggles ]

17:47.692 --> 17:50.278
So you didn't listen
to <i>any</i> of my concerns?

17:50.278 --> 17:51.862
Why are you just <i>now</i>
getting concerned?

17:51.862 --> 17:53.739
I found out in class
that Jacob teaches about

17:53.739 --> 17:56.367
Black historical figures
all year, not just February.

17:56.367 --> 17:58.411
Did you just start
paying attention this month?

18:01.998 --> 18:04.500
Oh. I didn't know that.

18:04.500 --> 18:07.044
Nor did I. Looks like
we both learned something today.

18:07.044 --> 18:08.838
[ Chuckles softly ]
Son.

18:10.715 --> 18:12.341
See you later.

18:12.341 --> 18:14.093
What a shame.

18:14.093 --> 18:16.429
So hot,
yet so very annoying.

18:19.765 --> 18:21.726
[ Door opens ]

18:21.726 --> 18:23.102
What's up, Amber?

18:23.102 --> 18:24.478
'Sup, Mo?

18:24.478 --> 18:26.397
Ooh, Telfar bag?!

18:26.397 --> 18:28.399
Happy Valentine's Day
to Janine!

18:28.399 --> 18:30.026
I hope you and Gregory
went shopping together.

18:30.026 --> 18:31.402
What are those?
Gel-X?

18:31.402 --> 18:33.112
Good eye.
Okay.

18:34.322 --> 18:37.033
Uh, hey. What's up?
What you doing here?

18:37.033 --> 18:38.701
I'm here to see Janine.
It's Valentine's Day.

18:38.701 --> 18:40.620
Duh.
Right.

18:40.620 --> 18:42.747
You think I just hang out
at schools for no reason, huh?

18:42.747 --> 18:44.373
Well, you ain't gotta wait here.
She's just down the hall.

18:44.373 --> 18:45.791
Thank you.
Yeah.

18:45.791 --> 18:47.752
Hi to you, too. Rude.

18:47.752 --> 18:49.462
Look. He got her
a Telfar bag.

18:50.379 --> 18:52.465
He...did.

18:53.758 --> 18:55.551
[ Knock on door ]

18:55.551 --> 18:56.761
Janine: Oh, hey!
Hey.

18:56.761 --> 18:59.138
I was just about
to come get you.

18:59.138 --> 19:00.765
Happy Valentine's Day.

19:00.765 --> 19:02.808
Oh, Mo!

19:02.808 --> 19:05.186
That's so sweet. Oh.

19:08.189 --> 19:09.523
What's wrong?
You don't like it?

19:09.523 --> 19:11.734
Um, no, I-I just --

19:11.734 --> 19:14.111
I think you forgot to put
the gift in the gift bag, so...

19:14.111 --> 19:16.781
No, the gift <i>is</i> the bag.

19:16.781 --> 19:18.449
Ohh! Oh, my God.

19:18.449 --> 19:21.327
It's so shiny, I thought
it was a shopping bag.

19:21.327 --> 19:23.120
But this is --
this is to put stuff in.

19:23.120 --> 19:24.413
Yeah.
Classic bag technology.

19:24.413 --> 19:26.248
Oh. Awesome. Wow!

19:26.248 --> 19:28.000
Well, careful, careful!

19:28.000 --> 19:29.460
Put the caps
on those pens, girl.

19:29.460 --> 19:30.795
That bag is expensive.
Oh.

19:30.795 --> 19:33.130
I love it.

19:33.130 --> 19:35.007
I hope you like it.
It's limited edition,

19:35.007 --> 19:36.926
so I had to go everywhere
to find it.

19:41.263 --> 19:43.015
Legos?

19:43.015 --> 19:45.351
Botanical Legos.
They're pretty.

19:45.351 --> 19:47.937
You know, since you're allergic
to real flowers.

19:47.937 --> 19:50.940
And this is for me,
not my kids?

19:50.940 --> 19:52.316
That was
the intention, yes.

19:54.860 --> 19:58.030
I say we get the kids involved,
we put that together...

19:58.030 --> 19:59.865
That bag look good
on you, girl.

19:59.865 --> 20:02.201
Aww. Thank you.
It's a Teflon.

20:02.201 --> 20:03.411
Maurice and Amber:
Telfar.

20:03.411 --> 20:04.662
Oh.

20:04.662 --> 20:06.455
Uh, your gift
is so cool.

20:06.455 --> 20:08.040
You're gonna have
so much fun with that.

20:09.834 --> 20:12.878
Well, Happy Valentine's Day,
Janine -- and Mo.

20:12.878 --> 20:16.257
Yeah. Happy Valentine's Day
to you two, too -- also.

20:22.138 --> 20:23.889
I purchased two tickets
to Atlantic City

20:23.889 --> 20:25.808
on Spirit Airlines,

20:25.808 --> 20:29.895
so Gerald and I are good to go
at Cibo's Bistro at the airport.

20:29.895 --> 20:31.063
Sweet.
Mm.

20:31.063 --> 20:32.022
You're welcome to join us.

20:32.022 --> 20:33.232
Nope. Mnh-mnh.

20:33.232 --> 20:34.817
Oh, we don't mind.

20:34.817 --> 20:37.528
Heck, the tickets
cost less than the meal.

20:37.528 --> 20:39.280
[ Chuckles ] No, no, no.
You two deserve a nice night

20:39.280 --> 20:41.031
to yourselves.
Don't worry about me.

20:41.031 --> 20:42.324
[ Cellphone buzzes ]
Okay.

20:42.324 --> 20:45.411
Hey. Look who finally
decided to text.

20:45.411 --> 20:47.329
Are you kidding me?
It's about work of all things.

20:47.329 --> 20:49.415
Gary wants me to take a picture
of the vending machine

20:49.415 --> 20:50.750
to see if we're running low
on Doritos.

20:50.750 --> 20:52.251
Yeah...

20:52.251 --> 20:54.170
I'm just making sure
that -- [ Gasps ]

20:54.170 --> 20:57.882
Aww! Gary!

20:57.882 --> 21:01.218
Welcome to
the coo-de-grass.

21:01.218 --> 21:04.305
Ohh! Well, it's "I..."
I something you.

21:04.305 --> 21:07.183
"I -- I owe you"?

21:08.184 --> 21:09.435
"I love you."

21:09.435 --> 21:11.103
I love you, too, Barb,
but -- Oh.

21:11.103 --> 21:13.647
Ohh! Is -- Is this --
You love me?

21:13.647 --> 21:16.192
Yeah! I love
the crap out of you.

21:16.192 --> 21:18.319
I love you, too,
you big <i>gavone!</i>

21:18.319 --> 21:20.279
Don't ever scare me
like that again!

21:20.279 --> 21:21.614
I won't. I won't.

21:25.743 --> 21:28.078
-- Captions by VITAC --
